When a small group of living things (a small population) separates from the main population from where they came from (for example, if they cross a chain of mountains or a river, or if they go to an island from which it is not possible to return easily), it often it seen in an environment different from that in which it lived before.
This new environment has different resources and new competitors, so the new population will need to acquire different characteristics of those that already possess and adapt to become a strong competitor.
The original population has not changed at all, they still need the same adaptations from before.
Over time, as the new population begins to adapt to its new environment, it becomes less and less like the other population.
Eventually, after thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will seem so different that they cannot be called the same species.
We call this process of speciation, which simply means the formation of new species. Speciation is an inevitable consequence and a very important part of evolution.
